nyc-combi-2435.explanation: The dog is being dressed up in human clothes to pretend that it is another child of the man. This is thus comparing the dog to a human child.

nyc-combi-2436.caption: When you're best in show, you can have nice clothes, too.
nyc-combi-2436.caption_hl: When you're best in show, you can have nice clothes, too.
nyc-combi-2436.explanation: The dog is rewarded with "nice clothes" for its good performance in show. It is rewarded as if it is a human being.

nyc-combi-2437.caption: You don't need a suit -- you're only seven. He's forty-nine.
nyc-combi-2437.caption_hl: You don't need a suit -- you're only seven. He's forty-nine.
nyc-combi-2437.explanation: The man treats the dog like a human being, dressing it up in a suit and saying it is "forty-nine" years old.

nyc-combi-2438.caption: He doesn't charge as much as he used to.
nyc-combi-2438.caption_hl: He doesn't charge as much as he used to.
nyc-combi-2438.conceptual_metaphor: Animals Are Humans / Humans Are Animals
nyc-combi-2438.explanation: The pun on "charge" is based on a metaphorical comparison between a bull and a (human) shop owner.

nyc-combi-2439.caption: I tend to complicate simple things.
nyc-combi-2439.explanation: A bull is hired as a shop assistant in a china shop. This is comparing the bull to a human being.

nyc-combi-2440.caption: Now he breaks stereotypes instead.
nyc-combi-2440.conceptual_metaphor: Humans Are Animals / Animals Are Humans; Ideas Are Objects
nyc-combi-2440.explanation: A bull works in a china shop (a metaphorical comparison between animals and humans), thus breaking the stereotype of bulls impulsively charging at everything and breaking things in a physical sense. The double meaning of "breaks" is thus based on a metaphor that compares mental images (stereotypes) with objects.

nyc-combi-2441.caption: Once I clarified what "break time" meant we haven't had any issues.
nyc-combi-2441.caption_hl: Once I clarified what "break time" meant we haven't had any issues.
nyc-combi-2441.conceptual_metaphor: Bull Is Employee / Employee Is Bull
nyc-combi-2441.explanation: The pun on "break time" is based on a metaphorical comparison between a bull and a human being (an employee).

nyc-combi-2442.caption: Things just weren't working out for him on Wall Street
nyc-combi-2442.caption_hl: Things just weren't working out for him on Wall Street
nyc-combi-2442.conceptual_metaphor: A Bull Is A Person; A Person Is A Bull
nyc-combi-2442.explanation: The shop owner hires a bull because there is no bull market on Wall Street. The joke uses a metaphor that compares a person with a bull.

nyc-combi-2443.caption: You were right—putting him on commission changed his attitude.

nyc-combi-2444.caption: Don't be fooled. He has a dark side.
nyc-combi-2444.caption_hl: Don't be fooled. He has a dark side.
nyc-combi-2444.explanation: The man warns the woman about the winking moon. The pun on "dark side" is thus based on a metaphor that compares the moon to a person.

nyc-combi-2445.caption: I think it's just a phase.
nyc-combi-2445.explanation: The moon winking is explained in a way that one would explain strange behaviors of a person. There is thus a metaphorical comparison between the moon and a person.

nyc-combi-2446.caption: No, no, no... you're definitely the first one I've brought up here.
nyc-combi-2446.caption_hl: No, no, no... you're definitely the first one I've brought up here.

nyc-combi-2447.caption: Remind me to close the curtains tonight.
nyc-combi-2447.caption_hl: Remind me to close the curtains tonight.
nyc-combi-2447.explanation: The caption acknowledges that the moon is winking. The joke is thus based on personification of the moon.

nyc-combi-2448.caption: When the moon's in the sky like a big winking eye, that's emoji.

nyc-combi-2449.caption: Wow, it's a rare full-of-himself moon.
nyc-combi-2449.explanation: The joke personifies the full moon by having it winking to the couple and describing it as "full of himself". The pun on "full of himself" is also based on a metaphor that compares one's mind to a container.
nyc-combi-2449.conceptual_metaphor: The Moon Is A Person; Mind Is A Container

nyc-combi-2513.caption: Hit me again with your cart and I'll hunt you down until the day I die.
nyc-combi-2513.caption_hl: Hit me again with your cart and I'll hunt you down until the day I die.
nyc-combi-2513.explanation: A whale is doing groceries at a supermarket and is threatened by a man. This is comparing the whale to a human being.

nyc-combi-2514.caption: If anyone asks, you're my support animal.
nyc-combi-2514.caption_hl: If anyone asks, you're my support animal.
nyc-combi-2514.explanation: The man is teaching the whale how to interact with others, as if the whale is a human being and speaks English.

nyc-combi-2515.caption: It was Melville who called you a dick.
nyc-combi-2515.caption_hl: It was Melville who called you a dick.
nyc-combi-2515.explanation: The whale is personified in this joke: it speaks English and is offended by being called a dick (Moby Dick).

nyc-combi-2516.caption: Oh I'm sorry, maybe I'd move faster if SOMEONE didn't bite my leg off.
nyc-combi-2516.caption_hl: Oh I'm sorry, maybe I'd move faster if SOMEONE didn't bite my leg off.
nyc-combi-2516.explanation: The joke is based on personification of the whale: It gets impatient waiting in a line in supermarket, and is mocked by the man in front of him.

nyc-combi-2517.caption: Oh, hey, I almost didn't recognize you outside of work.
nyc-combi-2517.caption_hl: Oh, hey, I almost didn't recognize you outside of work.
nyc-combi-2517.explanation: The man is speaking to the whale as if it is his colleague.

nyc-combi-2518.caption: Yeah, well, these are my obsession now.

nyc-combi-2525.caption: 'Yes Robert I bought a chair. I was sick of my options being between a rock and a hard place.'

nyc-combi-2526.caption: Do you want to go clubbing later?

nyc-combi-2527.caption: I can evolve.
nyc-combi-2527.explanation: The pun on "evolve" is based on a metaphorical comparison between personal development and biological evolution.

nyc-combi-2528.caption: I just can't get past the difference in our ages.
nyc-combi-2528.caption_hl: I just can't get past the difference in our ages.
nyc-combi-2528.explanation: The pun on "age" is based on a metaphorical comparison between a person's age and a period of history.

nyc-combi-2529.caption: If you're so civilized, why don't you use a coaster?

nyc-combi-2530.caption: The restroom is just down the hall and anywhere you want.

nyc-combi-2531.caption: And just when I finally got comfortable in my own skin, she repainted the bedroom.
nyc-combi-2531.caption_hl: And just when I finally got comfortable in my own skin, she repainted the bedroom.
nyc-combi-2531.explanation: The client is depicted as a chameleon. This metaphor use highlights the client's frustration when he is forced to adapt to a new environment, in an exaggerated way, thus achieving humor.

nyc-combi-2532.caption: Hmm. I'm beginning to see a pattern.
nyc-combi-2532.caption_hl: Hmm. I'm beginning to see a pattern.
nyc-combi-2532.explanation: The therapist's client is a chameleon. When he says he is beginning to see a pattern, he means the pattern on chameleon's skin ("pattern" in its literal sense) instead of what "pattern" usually means in such a context. The joke thus compares people with animals, and patterns in one's behavior to visual patterns.
nyc-combi-2532.conceptual_metaphor: People Are Animals; Behavioral Patterns Are Visual Patterns

nyc-combi-2533.caption: I'm referring you to another therapist. I'm afraid I can't see you any longer.
nyc-combi-2533.caption_hl: I'm referring you to another therapist. I'm afraid I can't see you any longer.
nyc-combi-2533.conceptual_metaphor: Meeting Someone Is Seeing Someone; People Are Animals
nyc-combi-2533.explanation: The therapist is having difficulty seeing his chameleon client, in the sense that he literally cannot see the chameleon as it changes its color and becomes invisible. The joke thus compares the chameleon with a (human) client, and meeting someone with seeing someone.

nyc-combi-2534.caption: Let's see how you feel on the curtains.

nyc-combi-2535.caption: So, you're saying you didn't miss your last two appointments?
nyc-combi-2535.caption_hl: So, you're saying you didn't miss your last two appointments?
nyc-combi-2535.explanation: The therapist thought his client (a chameleon) missed the last two appointments, while the chameleon actually came to the appointments but the therapist couldn't see it. The joke is thus based on a metaphor that compares the chameleon with a human client.
nyc-combi-2535.conceptual_metaphor: Animals Are Humans; Humans Are Animals

nyc-combi-2536.caption: Why am I always the one who needs to change?
nyc-combi-2536.caption_hl: Why am I always the one who needs to change?
nyc-combi-2536.explanation: The therapist's client is depicted as a chameleon, which gives rise to the pun on "change". The joke thus compares humans with animals, and changing one's behavior with changing one's appearance.
nyc-combi-2536.conceptual_metaphor: Humans Are Animals; Behavior Is Appearance

nyc-combi-2561.caption: He says I don't have to worry about returning the dish.
nyc-combi-2561.caption_hl: He says I don't have to worry about returning the dish.
nyc-combi-2561.explanation: The joke is based on personification of Death. Death is pictured as Grim Reaper and is handing a couple a plate of lemons.

nyc-combi-2562.caption: He says making lemonade is not an option.
nyc-combi-2562.explanation: Personification is used but the caption-and-image combination is not particularly funny.

nyc-combi-2563.caption: He's the only one who can legally hand out refreshments to voters in Georgia.
nyc-combi-2563.caption_hl: He's the only one who can legally hand out refreshments to voters in Georgia.
nyc-combi-2563.explanation: Death is personified and plays a role in elections.

nyc-combi-2564.caption: I do love a good twist.
nyc-combi-2564.conceptual_metaphor: Death Is A Person; Situation Is An Object
nyc-combi-2564.explanation: A pun on "twist" is based on personification of Death (receiving lemons from Death is a good twist) and a metaphorical comparison between a situation and an object that can be twisted.

nyc-combi-2565.caption: Of course it's farm to table, look at his scythe.
nyc-combi-2565.caption_hl: Of course it's farm to table, look at his scythe.
nyc-combi-2565.explanation: Death is personified and considered a farmer.

nyc-combi-2566.caption: They can't be any worse than the ones life gave us.
nyc-combi-2566.caption_hl: They can't be any worse than the ones life gave us.
nyc-combi-2566.conceptual_metaphor: Death Is A Person; Life Is A Person; Circumstances Are Tangible Objects
nyc-combi-2566.explanation: The joke is based on personification of life and death. The man indicates that he has received terrible things from life, and therefore he is prepared to receive anything from death.

nyc-combi-2567.caption: Do you have any experience working in a fast-paced environment?
nyc-combi-2567.caption_hl: Do you have any experience working in a fast-paced environment?
nyc-combi-2567.explanation: A fast-paced (working) environment is depicted as mice pacing fast in running wheels. There is thus a metaphorical comparison between animals and humans, and the pun on "fast-paced" uses a metaphor that compares working with running.
nyc-combi-2567.conceptual_metaphor: Animals Are Workers / Workers Are Animals; Working Is Running

nyc-combi-2568.caption: First, let me bring you up to speed.
nyc-combi-2568.caption_hl: First, let me bring you up to speed.
nyc-combi-2568.conceptual_metaphor: Animals Are Humans / Employees Are Animals
nyc-combi-2568.explanation: The animals are personified, which gives rise to the pun on "bring you up to speed": It is unclear whether the mouse wants feed the turtle with the latest information (the idiomatic meaning) or just wants it to be faster (the literal meaning).

nyc-combi-2569.caption: We're really looking for someone with more lab experience.
nyc-combi-2569.caption_hl: We're really looking for someone with more lab experience.
nyc-combi-2569.explanation: A mouse is rejecting a turtle's job application, because turtles typically have less "lab experience". The joke thus relies on a metaphorical comparison between animals and human beings.

nyc-combi-2570.caption: Well for starters, you were 4 days late to the interview.
nyc-combi-2570.caption_hl: Well for starters, you were 4 days late to the interview.
nyc-combi-2570.conceptual_metaphor: Animals Are Humans / Humans Are Animals
nyc-combi-2570.explanation: The mice are serious about their job of running on wheels, and they are firing a turtle because it is too slow: it did not even make it to the job interview. The joke is thus based on a metaphor that compares animals with different types of people.

nyc-combi-2571.caption: You will still get nowhere—it will just take longer.
nyc-combi-2571.caption_hl: You will still get nowhere—it will just take longer.
nyc-combi-2571.explanation: A mouse explains to a turtle that running on wheels can make it move faster, but it will still get nowhere. The joke is thus based on a metaphor that compares animals with humans.

nyc-combi-2572.caption: You're cold blooded. You belong in upper management.
nyc-combi-2572.explanation: The turtle is assigned to upper management in the company because it is cold blooded. There is a pun on "cold blooded", as it means both that turtles are literally cold-blooded animals and that people working in upper management are typically cold-blooded.
nyc-combi-2572.caption_hl: You're cold blooded. You belong in upper management.

nyc-combi-2573.caption: How long has the "Check Condiments" light been on?
nyc-combi-2573.explanation: A hotdog is used as a car, and condiments are the car's gasoline. That's why the driver is prompted to "Check Condiments" when the car runs out of gasoline.
nyc-combi-2573.caption_hl: How long has the "Check Condiments" light been on?

nyc-combi-2574.caption: So, when did the 'check mustard' light come on?
nyc-combi-2574.caption_hl: So, when did the 'check mustard' light come on?
nyc-combi-2574.explanation: A hotdog is used as a car, and mustard is the car's gasoline. The driver is prompted to check mustard when the car runs out of gasoline.

nyc-combi-2575.caption: When does it knock worst?
nyc-combi-2575.explanation: The joke lies in the hotdog being used as a car (and now it is broken).

nyc-combi-2576.caption: Yeah, they're great cars, but you don't want to see how they get made.
nyc-combi-2576.explanation: A metaphorical comparison between cars and hotdogs is used to imply a potentially disturbing car manufacturing process that is hidden behind the superior functionality of the cars. The comparison is unexpected and witty, provoking the worst imagination of the car manufacturing process, achieving satire in a light-hearted way.
nyc-combi-2576.caption_hl: Yeah, they're great cars, but you don't want to see how they get made.

nyc-combi-2577.caption: You can use the loaner corn dog while you wait. Can you drive a stick?
nyc-combi-2577.explanation: The joke relies on a metaphorical comparison between fast food and vehicles. To use a loaner corn dog, the driver needs to drive the stick.
nyc-combi-2577.caption_hl: You can use the loaner corn dog while you wait. Can you drive a stick?

nyc-combi-1744.caption: Wait till you see the check.
nyc-combi-1744.conceptual_metaphor: Money Is A Tangible Object (Amount Of Payment Is Size Of Check)
nyc-combi-1744.explanation: The waiter is implying that the customer will have to pay a check as large as the menu. This is comparing amount of money with the size of a tangible object.
